   ## Summary
   
   The bug is in the `str_format` function in `/work/src/be_strlib.c`. When the
   format string contains "%%", which should produce a literal '%' character,
   the code incorrectly tries to match it as a format specifier that requires an
   argument. This causes the error "bad argument #2 to 'format': no value" when
   calling `s.format("%%")`.
   
   The root cause is that after extracting the format mode with `get_mode`, the
   code checks if there are enough arguments (`if (index > top)`) BEFORE
   checking what the format specifier is. For "%%", the specifier is '%', which
   doesn't require an argument, but the check happens before recognizing this.
   
   ROOT CAUSE: `/work/src/be_strlib.c:515` - The code checks `if (index > top)`
   before examining the format specifier character. When processing "%%", it
   should recognize that '%' is a literal escape sequence that doesn't consume
   an argument, but instead it tries to validate that argument #2 exists,
   causing the error. The switch statement at line 519 also lacks a case for
   '%', so even if it passed the argument check, it would fall through to the
   default error case.
   
   LOCAL FIX: Insert the following code after line 513 (after `p = get_mode(p +
   1, mode);`) and before line 514:
   
   ```c
   if (*p == '%') {
       be_pushstring(vm, "%");
       concat2(vm);
       format = p + 1;
       continue;
   }
   ```
   
   This checks if the format specifier is '%' (indicating "%%"), and if so,
   pushes a literal "%" character, concatenates it to the result, advances the
   format pointer, and continues the loop without incrementing the index
   variable (since "%%"doesn't consume an argument).
   
   GLOBAL FIX: The format string parsing should use a more robust state machine
   or parser that handles escape sequences as a distinct category from format
   specifiers. Instead of parsing '%' and then checking what follows, the code
   should:
   1. Use an explicit enum or type to classify format sequence types
   (FORMAT_ESCAPE, FORMAT_SPECIFIER)
   2. Have `get_mode` return this type along with the parsed mode string
   3. Only check for arguments when the type is FORMAT_SPECIFIER
   4. Consider using a table-driven approach where each format type (including
   '%') has metadata indicating whether it consumes an argument
   
   Alternatively, adopt a format string library (like printf-style formatting
   from a standard library) that already handles these cases correctly, rather
   than reimplementing format string parsing from scratch.

